# Human-testable deliverables

## Principle

If a human cannot run it from the repo and see a clear result, do not ship it as
the primary way to verify behavior.

Prefer **runnable Yarn commands** with visible output over library-only recipes or
documentation-only instructions.

## Do

- Provide runnable entry points: `yarn fetch-mirrors`,
  `yarn retrieve-history`, `yarn merge-queue`, `yarn sync`, `yarn test`,
  and `yarn typecheck`
- Document how to run in [`docs/run-local.md`](../docs/run-local.md) (copy-paste,
  run, read `[sync]` / `[PASS]` / counts / tables)
- Run the same command yourself before telling the user something works
- Print progress and summary so success is obvious

## Do not

- Do not make importing lib modules the main test path
- Do not split a pipeline into numbered Step01/Step02 scripts or opaque test
  harnesses; use named Yarn scripts that run directly
- Do not write docs that only say "load functions" with no runnable command
- Do not claim verification without running the command in this environment

## Docs

- [`docs/run-local.md`](../docs/run-local.md): how a human runs sync locally
- [`docs/PLAN.md`](../docs/PLAN.md): design; link to run-local for try-it commands

## Agent behavior

- After implementing sync logic, run the relevant command (`yarn fetch-mirrors`,
  `yarn retrieve-history`, `yarn merge-queue`, `yarn sync`, `yarn test`,
  or `yarn typecheck`) and report
  actual output (counts, errors)
- Use `--skip-fetch` when mirrors already exist under `.work/mirrors/`
